***************************************************************************
@NODE r "requirements"
@{LINDENT 1}



@{B}requirements@{UB}



CPUSpd should  work fine  on any  ECS/AGA Amiga  equipped with  at least  a
MC68020 CPU and KS 2.04.
@ENDNODE



***************************************************************************
@NODE d "description"
@{LINDENT 1}



@{B}description@{UB}



This little  proggie returns  the clock  frequency of  the MC68k  processor
mounted on your  Amiga and some  statistics in relation  to video  refresh.
I really wonder whoever needs it!
Yet, in the  past, several people  seemed to  like it (still  sounds a  bit
strange), which made me release a few updates.

The output looks like this:

  @{B}CPUSpd@{UB}

  CPU: MC68030
  FPU: N/A
  CPU cycles per raster line (451): 1606
  CPU cycles per frame (70 Hz): 724340
  CPU clock frequency: 50.7 MHz

 ° line #1 shows which processor is mounted on your machine
 ° line #2 shows the floating point unit, which can be:
   - N/A, if none is present
   - MC68881/MC68882, if there's an MC6888x math co-processor
   -  MC68040/MC68060,  if   the  processor   mounted  is   one  of   these
 ° line #3 shows the number of cycles done by the CPU each time a rasterline
   of the screen is redrawn (the number of rasterlines per frame is enclosed
   in the brackets)
 ° line #4 gives the amount of cycles performed by the CPU during  1/XX -th
   of second,  where  XX indicates  the  screen refresh  frequency  of  the
   current video mode (indicated in the brackets)
 ° line #5 tells the speed of the processor
@ENDNODE



***************************************************************************
@NODE u "usage"
@{LINDENT 1}



@{B}usage@{UB}



CPUSpd is  a single  file program  so  it needs  no installation:  copy  it
wherever you like (f.ex. C:).

Run it from shell only;
the template is:

 RETCOD/S,QUIET/S

where:

 RETCOD = tells  CPUSpd to return  the CPU frequency  (expressed in Hz)  as
          returncode (negative value in case of error)
 QUIET = do not print any output

Check the @{"notes" LINK mn} and @{"bugs" LINK b&t} sections if you have any problem.
@ENDNODE



***************************************************************************
@NODE mn "miscellaneous notes"
@{LINDENT 1}



@{B}miscellaneous notes@{UB}



@{U}approximation@{UU}

The values  returned are  slightly approximate,  yet they  should be  quite
close to real values.
Fluctuations on least significant digits may occur.



@{U}MC68060@{UU}

This was definitely the CPU which  gave me more problems (mainly because  I
do not own  a MC68060  to experiment with);  yet, I  eventually managed  to
make CPUSpd run properly also on this processor.
Should CPUSpd fail to work correctly, please try:

 1. [re-]boot without startup-sequence
 2. run SetPatch
 3. run CPUSpd 



@{U}system friendliness@{UU}

The operating system  activity is  completely stopped for  the duration  of
the test (just few frames), so make  sure that there is no particular  task
going on when starting CPUSpd.
On exit the system is cleanly restored.



@{U}screen modes notes@{UU}

The number of scanlines and the  video refresh rate are calculated by  some
nasty routines which directly  hit the HW (no  OS function has been  used).

Some interlaced screen modes seem to perform interlacing without using  the
VERTB interrupt,  thus  fooling CPUSpd's  routines  used to  calculate  the
frame duration: the result is that sometimes the speed test lasts twice  as
normal, and so the calculated  CPU speed turns out  to be exactly twice  as
big... can't do much to fix this, sorry!

Since all  the calculations  are relative  to native  video modes,  strange
results may be  output on graphic  card equipped Amigas  (depending on  how
the native chipset is treated by software drivers).
Sometimes CPUSpd has performed well anyway, but surely the values  returned
do not refer to the graphic card display.
@ENDNODE



***************************************************************************
@NODE b&t "bugs & testing"
@{LINDENT 1}



@{B}bugs & testing@{UB}

I thought  that the  previous versions  were totally  bug-free, but  I  was
wrong bigtime.  I can't  assure  you that  this  version will  run  without
problems on your equipment,  but I still can  tell you which machines  this
program has been successfully tested on:

 - A1200 (MC68EC020@14)
 - A1200 + Bz1230 (MC68030@50)
 - A2000 + Bz2060 (MC68060@50) + CV64/3D (CGX 4)
 - A4000 + CS MKIII (MC68060@50) + CV64/3D (CGX 3.0)

previous versions were also tested on:

 - A500 (MC68000@36) - yes, 36 MHz! :o
 - A1200 + Bz1260 (MC68060@50)
 - A4000 (MC68040@25)



If you experience any problem, maybe  you'll find an answer @{"here" LINK mn}; in  case
you still  can't get  my  program to  run properly,  then  @{"drop me a line" LINK c},
reporting your system's configuration and,  if possible, the shell  output.



Here you can find the  results of several tests  I performed on my  machine
(note that I  use patched monitor  drivers and thus  the frequencies  shown
are correct):

